  { question: 'How do I backwash a filter straw on the trail?', answer: 'If your filter supports backwashing (check the instructions), you reverse the water flow through the membrane to push out trapped particles. The NatureNova kit includes a dedicated backwash syringe. For straws without a syringe, you can improvise by blowing air forcefully back through the outlet end over a sink or away from clean water. Backwash when flow rate drops noticeably — typically after filtering 20-50 liters of sediment-heavy water.' },
  { question: 'Can I use a filter straw with a hydration bladder?', answer: 'Not directly inline with most hydration bladders, but you can use a filter straw to fill your bladder. Filter water from a stream into a clean container, then pour it into your bladder. Some hikers carry a small squeeze bag to filter water quickly into their bladder reservoir. This is faster than drinking directly and lets you carry pre-filtered water between sources.' },
