  <h2>Why Hikers Need Dedicated Water Filtration</h2>
  <p>Carrying all the water you need for a full day of hiking is heavy and impractical. One liter of water weighs 2.2 pounds, which means a full day's supply of 3-4 liters adds nearly 9 pounds to your pack. On multi-day backpacking trips, this equation becomes impossible — you simply cannot carry enough.</p>
  <p>The solution is to carry a lightweight filter and refill from natural sources along the trail. A filter straw weighing just 2 ounces replaces pounds of carried water and provides access to thousands of liters of safe drinking water from streams, lakes, and springs throughout your hike.</p>
  <p>The risk of drinking unfiltered backcountry water is well documented. A study published in the journal <em>Wilderness & Environmental Medicine</em> found that Giardia cysts were present in over 50% of backcountry water sources tested in popular hiking areas. Symptoms of giardiasis include severe diarrhea, cramps, and nausea lasting 2-6 weeks — a hike-ending and potentially dangerous condition, especially in remote areas far from medical care.</p>

  <h2>What to Look For in a Hiking Water Filter</h2>
  <p>Hikers have specific needs that differ from casual campers. Here are the criteria that matter most on the trail:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Weight:</strong> The most critical factor. Anything over 4 ounces is too heavy for ultralight setups. The best filter straws weigh 2-2.5 ounces — lighter than most energy bars.</li>
    <li><strong>Pack size:</strong> A hiking filter should fit in a hip belt pocket or side mesh pocket. Straws roughly the size of a thick marker are ideal. Avoid bulky pump systems.</li>
    <li><strong>Flow rate:</strong> Hiking filters sacrifice speed for portability. Expect to spend 30-60 seconds filling a liter through a straw, compared to seconds from a gravity system. This tradeoff is worth it for the weight savings.</li>
    <li><strong>Durability:</strong> Trail filters get bounced around in packs, dropped on rocks, and used in cold weather. Look for rugged construction and membranes that can handle the abuse of trail life.</li>
    <li><strong>Ease of use while moving:</strong> The best hiking filters work with minimal setup. Being able to dip a straw into a stream and drink immediately keeps you moving.</li>
  </ul>

