  <h2>Hiking-Specific Water Filtration Tips</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Plan water stops ahead of time:</strong> Study your trail map for reliable water sources and plan refills accordingly. Carrying an extra half-liter between unreliable sources is better than running dry.</li>
    <li><strong>Filter upstream from trail crossings:</strong> Collect water above where the trail crosses a stream. Below the crossing, sediment and contaminants are stirred up by hikers and pack animals.</li>
    <li><strong>Never let your filter freeze:</strong> Sleep with your filter straw inside your sleeping bag in cold weather. Frozen membranes develop invisible microcracks that allow pathogens through. If you suspect your filter froze, discard it and use Aquatabs instead.</li>
    <li><strong>Carry a pre-filter:</strong> A bandana or coffee filter weighs almost nothing and removes large debris before it clogs your straw. This dramatically extends filter life on muddy water sources.</li>
    <li><strong>Use the buddy system:</strong> If hiking with a partner, each carry a filter straw. Redundancy is critical when you are days from a trailhead and dependent on natural water sources.</li>
  </ul>

